<hr />
<h2 id="a-brief-history-of-each-format">A Brief History of Each Format</h2>
<p>EPUB was created by the International Digital Publishing Forum (IDPF) and reached version 2.0 in 2007, replacing the earlier Open eBook format. The standard was designed from the start as a reflowable, open alternative to proprietary formats like Amazon's MOBI and Microsoft's LIT. EPUB 3.0 followed in 2011, adding native support for audio, video, interactivity, and richer typography. In 2017, the IDPF merged with the W3C, and EPUB maintenance moved under the same body that governs HTML and CSS — making EPUB effectively a sibling format to the web standards that power most online reading today.</p>
<p>PDF was released by Adobe in 1993 as a way to share documents across different computers, operating systems, and printers without losing formatting. The "portable" in Portable Document Format refers to that goal: a file would look identical on a Mac in 1993, a Windows PC in 2003, and an iPhone in 2023. Adobe donated the full PDF specification to the International Organization for Standardization in 2008, and PDF 1.7 became ISO 32000-1:2008. The format has been updated in stages since — PDF 2.0 arrived as ISO 32000-2 in 2017, with stronger encryption, tagged accessibility improvements, and richer metadata for document workflows.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="use-cases-by-audience">Use Cases by Audience</h2>
<p>Pick your role and the choice usually makes itself:</p>
<table>
