<td>PDF</td>
<td>Stable citations, easy highlighting, prints cleanly for handwritten notes</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Authors (self-publishing)</td>
<td>EPUB</td>
<td>Reflows on every device, sells on Apple Books, Kobo, and Google Play from one file</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Business professionals</td>
<td>PDF</td>
<td>Contracts, invoices, and signed forms need fixed layout and signature fields</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Casual readers</td>
<td>EPUB</td>
<td>Ereaders and reading apps are built around it, with adjustable fonts and themes</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Archivists and librarians</td>
<td>PDF (PDF/A)</td>
<td>ISO-standardized profile designed for long-term preservation</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>The general rule: if your reader will mostly <em>read</em> the file, EPUB. If they'll <em>sign, print, archive, or share</em> it, PDF.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="faq">FAQ</h2>
<h3 id="can-kindle-read-pdf">Can Kindle read PDF?</h3>
<p>Yes. Every Kindle from the last decade — the basic Kindle, Paperwhite, Oasis, and Scribe — opens PDF files. Email them to your Kindle address, sideload over USB, or read in the Kindle app. The catch is comfort: PDFs display at their original page size, so a US Letter document on a 6-inch screen means constant zooming and panning. For anything longer than a quick reference, convert the PDF to EPUB first.</p>
<h3 id="does-epub-work-on-all-phones">Does EPUB work on all phones?</h3>
<p>Mostly yes. iPhones and iPads open EPUB files natively in Apple Books. Android phones open them through Google Play Books or any third-party reader from the Play Store. The gap: Amazon's Kindle app reads Kindle formats (AZW, KFX) directly and accepts EPUB only through the "Send to Kindle" service, which converts the file. Windows phones are gone, so that's no longer a concern.</p>
<h3 id="which-is-better-for-academic-papers">Which format is better for academic papers?</h3>
<p>PDF, almost always. Academic papers rely on exact column layouts, figure placement, footnotes, equation numbering, and citation formatting. Reflowing one into EPUB usually breaks two-column layouts, scrambles figures relative to their captions, and turns footnotes into a navigation headache. PDF also handles Zotero, Mendeley, and EndNote integrations cleanly, prints exactly as the journal intends, and is what most preprint servers — arXiv, bioRxiv, SSRN — distribute in.</p>
<h3 id="can-i-read-an-epub-on-a-kindle">Can I read an EPUB on a Kindle?</h3>
<p>Yes, with one step. Drag the EPUB into the Send to Kindle web app, or email it to your Kindle address with the subject line "convert." Amazon's server converts it to a Kindle format (KFX or AZW3) and delivers it within a minute or two. Calibre, the free desktop ebook manager, handles the same job locally and gives you finer control over formatting, metadata, and covers.</p>
<h3 id="is-pdf-more-secure-than-epub">Is PDF more secure than EPUB?</h3>
<p>PDF has stronger built-in security. The spec supports 128-bit and 256-bit AES encryption, owner and user passwords, and per-feature permissions (print, copy, edit, annotate). Most PDF readers respect these. EPUB supports DRM through the LCP and Adobe ACS schemes, but adoption is patchy — many EPUBs ship with no DRM, and the apps vary in how strictly they enforce it. For confidential business documents or legal contracts, PDF is the safer default. If you are converting documents online and want to understand how your data is handled, read our <a href="/blog/epub-converter-privacy/">online converter privacy and safety guide</a>.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="the-bottom-line">The Bottom Line</h2>
<p><strong>Use EPUB for reading.</strong> If you're an author publishing an ebook, a reader building a library, or anyone consuming long-form content on a variety of devices, EPUB is the format built for you.</p>
<p><strong>Use PDF for everything else.</strong> When formatting fidelity, printability, annotation, or universal compatibility matters more than the reading experience, PDF is the right tool.</p>
